1
00:00:00,833 --> 00:00:02,291
And here was the first group cell

2
00:00:05,250 --> 00:00:08,041
This is the first group cell, where I was imprisoned twice

3
00:00:10,500 --> 00:00:14,500
The first time I stayed for four days, not counting
this whole period of imprisonment I’m describing

4
00:00:14,750 --> 00:00:16,750
Here were all the prisoners’ memories

5
00:00:17,416 --> 00:00:21,666
I was imprisoned here with someone named Abdul Razzaq al-Barish

6
00:00:22,166 --> 00:00:26,833
I was released, but he wasn’t. He and his brother Faisal were killed

7
00:00:27,166 --> 00:00:28,500
We were imprisoned here together

8
00:00:29,416 --> 00:00:31,666
And here my father and all my brothers were imprisoned

9
00:00:32,708 --> 00:00:35,166
There was an electrical socket on this wall

10
00:00:35,708 --> 00:00:40,250
We used it to communicate with group cell four,
whose door is far from here. We’ll see it shortly

11
00:00:40,750 --> 00:00:45,541
We communicated from here, as there was a power
socket, and through it we could talk to each other

12
00:00:45,958 --> 00:00:50,416
Just by hearing a knock on the
wall, we knew a prisoner wanted to talk

13
00:00:50,458 --> 00:00:53,666
We would immediately come here and
speak to him, and the sound would be clear

14
00:00:53,708 --> 00:00:56,458
Interviewer: What was the most
striking phrase you saw written here in the prison?

15
00:01:01,125 --> 00:01:05,541
As I told you, there was a man named
Abu Madian, who influenced me the most

16
00:01:06,125 --> 00:01:08,625
They erased all his writings in the other group cells

17
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:11,208
But here he had a small inscription

18
00:01:11,916 --> 00:01:17,041
It was written here, though I don’t know if
it’s still visible. He wrote his son’s name

19
00:01:17,833 --> 00:01:18,833
This is Madian

20
00:01:20,458 --> 00:01:26,041
He used to write on the pillows and mattresses—wherever
you went, you’d find the names Madian and Abu Madian

21
00:01:26,625 --> 00:01:29,541
His real name was Muhammad al-Hateel, known as Abu Madian

22
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:33,041
He had spent 110 days in prison

23
00:01:34,208 --> 00:01:35,208
And he was killed

24
00:01:37,333 --> 00:01:39,333
He was a calligrapher, may God have mercy on him

25
00:01:43,708 --> 00:01:48,750
Interviewer: Who were the people with you in
the group cell, if you still remember them?

26
00:01:49,041 --> 00:01:52,750
In this group cell, Hassan al-Ibrahim was imprisoned with me

27
00:01:53,625 --> 00:01:54,958
Hassan Ibrahim al-Sheikh

28
00:01:55,708 --> 00:01:59,708
Walid al-Hajji and Mutasim al-Hajji

29
00:02:00,250 --> 00:02:02,625
And Muhammad Abdul Fattah al-Oweihi

30
00:02:03,541 --> 00:02:07,708
And Ghanem al-Ibrahim. We were imprisoned together,
along with several others whose names I’ve forgotten

31
00:02:07,958 --> 00:02:11,166
Witness: But I’ve forgotten their names. Interviewer:
Do you have any writing on the prison walls?

32
00:02:11,291 --> 00:02:14,125
I didn’t write anything myself, but
there’s a note from my brother Ibrahim

33
00:02:14,125 --> 00:02:18,125
We were imprisoned together for a while.
That’s his name here—Ibrahim al-Salama

34
00:02:24,166 --> 00:02:26,083
He also has another name written here

35
00:02:26,750 --> 00:02:28,166
And I didn’t write anything here

36
00:02:30,625 --> 00:02:35,750
Most of my writings were in the solitary cells
because I spent most of my imprisonment there

37
00:02:36,208 --> 00:02:38,958
They painted the walls so no one could recognize

38
00:02:40,041 --> 00:02:41,875
What happened to the prisoners
